#* {{RQ:Churchill Celebrity|chapter=5|passage=When this conversation was repeated in detail within the hearing of the young woman in question, and undoubtedly for his '''benefit''', Mr. Trevor threw shame to the winds and scandalized the Misses Brewster then and there by proclaiming his father to have been a country storekeeper.}}
# {{lb|en|insurance}} A [[payment]] made in [[accordance]] with an [[insurance]] [[policy]] or a [[public]] [[assistance]] [[scheme]].
# An [[event]] such as a [[performance]], given to [[raise]] [[fund]]s for some [[cause]].
# {{lb|en|obsolete}} [[beneficence]]; [[liberality]]
#* {{RQ:Webster Malfi|scene=v|page=65|passage=The Birds, that liue i'th field / On the wilde '''Benefit''' of nature, liue / Happier then we; for they may chooſe their Mates, / And carroll their ſweet pleaſures to the Spring: {{...}}}}
# Intended audience (as ''for the benefit of''). 
#: {{ux|en|The whole scene was staged for his '''benefit''', and it completely fooled him.}}
#: {{ux|en|Since my wife is Canadian, whenever we have dinner with my family, they keep bringing up anything they've heard about Canada lately for her '''benefit.'''}}
#* {{quote-web|en|title=''Succession de Kalimbet Piela c. Obodzinski,'' 2020 QCCS 1222 |author=Gary D.D. Morrison, J.|url=https://canlii.ca/t/j6gqs|work=CanLII|date=16 April 2020|accessdate=9 May 2021|text=So, if Obodzinski is correct in saying that Mrs. Piela actually signed a document in the coffee shop, in front of witnesses, she staged a scene, pretending that it was the alleged Mandate. The other explanation is that none of this ever took place, and the staging was only a fictitious creation for the '''benefit''' of the Court.}}

